or the k k -th propagation path, determined by the reflection coefficients of the six walls. ρ k {{\\rho_{k}}} is the length between the image source and the error microphone for the k k -th propagation path, which depends on the room geometry and the locations of the noise source and the error microphone. K K is the total number of propagation paths between the noise and the error microphone, c a c_{\\rm{a}} is the sound speed in air, T s T_{\\rm s} is the sampling period, ⌊ ⋅ ⌋ \\left\\lfloor\\cdot\\right\\rfloor is the floor function, and δ ​ ( ⋅ ) \\delta(\\cdot) is the Dirac delta function. Similarly, the RIR between the noise source and the j j -th reference microphone is stated as q j ​ ( n ) = ∑ m = 1 M j β j , m ​ δ ​ ( n − n j , m ) 4 ​ π ​ υ j , m , j = 1 , 2 , … , J , {q_{j}}(n)=\\sum\\limits_{m=1}^{{M_{j}}}{{\\beta_{j,m}}\\frac{{\\delta(n-{n_{j,m}})}}{{4\\pi{\\upsilon_{j,m}}}}},\\quad j=1,2,\\ldots,J, (19) where n j , m = ⌊ υ j , m c a ​ T s ⌋ {n_{j,m}}=\\left\\lfloor{\\frac{{{\\upsilon_{j,m}}}}{{c_{\\rm{a}}T_{\\rm s}}}}\\right\\rfloor . β j , m {{\\beta_{j,m}}} is the gain for the m m -th propagation path for the j j -th reference microphone. υ j , m {{\\upsilon_{j,m}}} is the length between the image source and the j j -th reference microphone for the m m -th propagation path. M j M_{j} is the total number of propagation paths between the noise and the j j -th reference microphone. The discrete-time Fourier transform of Eqs. ( 18 ) and ( 19 ) can be written as P ​ ( ω ) = ∑ k = 1 K α k ​ e − i ​ ω c a ​ ρ k 4 ​ π ​ ρ k , P(\\omega)=\\sum\\limits_{k=1}^{K}{{\\alpha_{k}}\\frac{{{e^{-i\\frac{\\omega}{c_{\\rm{a}}}{\\rho_{k}}}}}}{{4\\pi{\\rho_{k}}}}}, (20) Q j ​ ( ω ) = ∑ m = 1 M j β j , m ​ e − i ​ ω c a ​ υ j , m 4 ​ π ​ υ j , m , j = 1 , 2 , … , J , Q_{j}(\\omega)=\\sum\\limits_{m=1}^{M_{j}}{{\\beta_{j,m}}\\frac{{{e^{-i\\frac{\\omega}{c_{\\rm{a}}}{\\upsilon_{j,m}}}}}}{{4\\pi{\\upsilon_{j,m}}}}},\\quad j=1,2,\\ldots,J, (21) where i = − 1 i=\\sqrt{-1} . Substituting Eqs. ( 20 ) and ( 21 ) into Eq. ( 17 ), the frequency response of the j j -th optimal control filter W j o ​ ( ω ) W_{j}^{o}(\\omega) can be rewritten as W j o ​ ( ω ) \\displaystyle W_{j}^{o}(\\omega) = P ​ ( ω ) S ​ ( ω ) ​ Q j ∗ ​ ( ω ) ∑ u = 1 J | Q u ​ ( ω ) | 2 \\displaystyle=\\frac{{P(\\omega)}}{{S(\\omega)}}\\frac{{Q_{j}^{*}(\\omega)}}{{\\sum\\limits_{u=1}^{J}{{{\\left|{{Q_{u}}(\\omega)}\\right|}^{2}}}}} (22) = ∑ k = 1 K α k ​ e − i ​ ω c a ​ ρ k 4 ​ π ​ ρ k S ​ ( ω ) × ∑ m = 1 M j β j , m ​ e i ​ ω c a ​ υ j , m 4 ​ π ​ υ j , m ∑ u = 1 J ∑ m = 1 M u ∑ m ′ = 1 M u β u , m ​ β u , m ′ ​ e − i ​ ω c a ​ ( υ u , m − υ u , m ′ ) ( 4 ​ π ) 2 ​ υ u , m ​ υ u , m ′ . \\displaystyle=\\frac{{\\sum\\limits_{k=1}^{K}{{\\alpha_{k}}\\frac{{{e^{-i\\frac{\\omega}{c_{\\rm{a}}}{\\rho_{k}}}}}}{{4\\pi{\\rho_{k}}}}}}}{{S(\\omega)}}\\times\\frac{{\\sum\\limits_{m=1}^{{M_{j}}}{{\\beta_{j,m}}\\frac{{{e^{i\\frac{\\omega}{c_{\\rm{a}}}{\\upsilon_{j,m}}}}}}{{4\\pi{\\upsilon_{j,m}}}}}}}{{\\sum\\limits_{u=1}^{J}{\\sum\\limits_{m=1}^{{M_{u}}}{\\sum\\limits_{{m^{\\prime}}=1}^{{M_{u}}}{{\\beta_{u,m}}{\\beta_{u,{m^{\\prime}}}}\\frac{{{e^{-i\\frac{\\omega}{c_{\\rm{a}}}({\\upsilon_{u,m}}-{\\upsilon_{u,{m^{\\prime}}}})}}}}{{{{(4\\pi)}^{2}}{\\upsilon_{u,m}}{\\upsilon_{u,{m^{\\prime}}}}}}}}}}}. From Eq. ( 22 ), it can be seen that, for a multi-reference ANC system operating in a specific reverberant environment, the location of the noise source plays a critical role. When the locations of the reference microphones and the error microphone are fixed, the noise source location determines the propagation path lengths for both the primary path ( ρ k \\rho_{k} ) and the reference paths ( υ j , m \\upsilon_{j,m} , υ u , m \\upsilon_{u,m} and υ u , m ′ \\upsilon_{u,m^{\\prime}} ), therefore jointly influencing the frequency response of the optimal control filter. In other words, the optimal control filter depends on the distance, elevation angle, and azimuth angle of the noise source relative to the reference microphones. Therefore, if the noise source location varies over time in a reverberant environment, using a fixed pre-trained control filter may result in degraded noise reduction performance. It is thus essential to employ a control filter that is suitable for the noise source location to achieve effective noise reduction. Figure 2: Block diagram of the proposed SF-GFANC method. A co-processor executes the CRNN to perform distance, elevation angle, azimuth angle classifications, and combination weights regression, followed by control filter generation for each noise frame. In parallel, real-time noise control is performed at the sampling rate. The error microphone is used solely to monitor noise reduction performance and is not involved in the control filter update process. 4 The Proposed SF-GFANC Method This section details the proposed SF-GFANC method. To translate the theoretical spatial dependency established in Section 3 into a practical implementation, the proposed framework approximates this dependency by explicitly constructing a spatially sampled control filter library and employing a multi-task CRNN for the estimation of spatial cues. As illustrated in Fig. 2 , the co-processor and the real-time controller operate in parallel at different rates to enable delayless noise control. Specifically, the generated control filter incorporates both spatial and frequency cues of the noise source, enabling effective attenuation of noise sources with various 3D locations and frequency characteristics in reverberant environments. 4.1 Pre-trained Control Filter Library Prior to the online execution of the SF-GFANC method, a control filter library must be pre-trained to accommodate noise sources located at various 3D locations. Specifically, the noise sources are placed on spherical grids surrounding the reference microphone array center, defined by A A discrete distances, B B elevation angles, and C C azimuth angles. The values of A A , B B , and C C represent a trade-off between spatial resolution and storage cost and can be adjusted according to system requirements. At each grid point, a control filter [ 𝐰 a , b , c ] a = 1 , b = 1 , c = 1 A , B , C ∈ ℝ 1 × J ​ L c \\left[{{{\\bf{w}}^{a,b,c}}}\\right]_{a=1,b=1,c=1}^{A,B,C}\\in\\mathbb{R}{{}^{1\\times JL_{\\rm c}}} is pre-trained for a broadband white noise using the FxLMS algorithm described in Section 2.2 . The resulting control filters are stored in a library for subsequent deployment during online noise control. 4.2 CRNN for Spatial-Frequency Cues Estimation Subsequently, a CRNN is trained using a multi-task learning strategy to perform distance, elevation angle, and azimuth angle classifications, along with combination weights regression. These spatial-frequency cues jointly guide the generation of the appropriate control filter. 4.2.1 CRNN Architecture The architecture of the proposed CRNN is illustrated in Fig. 3 . Instead of employing an explicit feature extraction pipeline, the short-time Fourier transform (STFT) is applied for data preprocessing, allowing the convolutional layers to learn the spatial and frequency characteristics directly from data. Specifically, the STFT is computed for each frame of the J J -channel reference signal 𝐫 ∈ ℝ J × L r {{\\bf{r}}}\\in\\mathbb{R}{{}^{J\\times L_{\\rm r}}} , denoted as STFT ( 𝐫 ) ∈ ℂ J × F × T \\text{STFT}({\\bf{r}})\\in\\mathbb{C}{{}^{J\\times F\\times T}} , where L r L_{\\rm r} is the number of samples, F F is the number of frequency bins and T T is the number of time frames. From the STFT output, both the magnitude map | STFT ( 𝐫 ) | ∈ ℝ J × F × T \\left|{{\\rm{STFT}}({\\bf{r}})}\\right|\\in\\mathbb{R}{{}^{J\\times F\\times T}} and phase map ∠ STFT ( 𝐫 ) ∈ ℝ J × F × T \\angle{\\rm{STFT}}({\\bf{r}})\\in\\mathbb{R}{{}^{J\\times F\\times T}} are computed. These are then concatenated along the channel dimension to form a 2 ​ J × F × T 2J\\times F\\times T tensor and fed into the CRNN. To extract spatial and spectral features, the pre-processed input is passed through three convolutional blocks, each comprising a two-dimensional (2D) convolutional layer, group normalization, ReLU activation, and max-poolin", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false, "persistedOutputPath": "/inspire/qb-ilm/project/video-generation/chenxie-25019/hyr/iHateTheWorld555.github.io/.claude-review/projects/-inspire-qb-ilm-project-video-generation-chenxie-25019-hyr-iHateTheWorld555-github-io/75aedf01-d1ed-4e27-b84b-5886640ead7c/tool-results/br80kv18j.txt", "persistedOutputSize": 51393}}
