ically developed. In this section, it is shown that the conventional path-based expression can be reformulated into an explicit dependence on 3D spatial parameters, including distance, elevation angle, and azimuth angle, thereby providing a principled basis for 3D spatially conditioned control filter design. The analysis assumes that the locations of the reference microphones, secondary source, and error microphone are fixed. The error signal in the frequency domain is represented as E ​ ( ω ) = D ​ ( ω ) − S ​ ( ω ) ​ 𝐖 ​ ( ω ) ​ 𝐑 ​ ( ω ) , E(\\omega)=D(\\omega)-S(\\omega)\\bf{W}(\\omega)\\bf{R}(\\omega), (8) where D ​ ( ω ) D(\\omega) is the frequency response of the disturbance, S ​ ( ω ) S(\\omega) is the secondary path, 𝐖 ( ω ) ∈ ℂ 1 × J \\mathbf{W}(\\omega)\\in\\mathbb{C}{{}^{1\\times J}} is the control filter, with ℂ 1 × J \\mathbb{C}{{}^{1\\times J}} representing a 1 × J 1\\times J vector of complex values, and 𝐑 ( ω ) ∈ ℂ J × 1 \\mathbf{R}(\\omega)\\in\\mathbb{C}{{}^{J\\times 1}} is the reference signal. To find the optimal control filter, the cost function is the power spectral density (PSD) of the error signal, given by J ​ ( ω ) \\displaystyle J(\\omega) = C d ​ d ​ ( ω ) − 𝐂 𝐫 ​ d ​ ( ω ) ​ 𝐖 H ​ ( ω ) ​ S ​ ( ω ) ∗ − S ​ ( ω ) ​ 𝐖 ​ ( ω ) ​ 𝐂 𝐫 ​ d H ​ ( ω ) \\displaystyle={{C}_{dd}}(\\omega)-{{\\bf{C}}_{{\\bf{r}}d}}(\\omega)\\mathbf{W}^{\\mathrm{H}}(\\omega)S(\\omega)^{*}-S(\\omega)\\mathbf{W}(\\omega){{\\bf{C}}^{\\mathrm{H}}_{{\\bf{r}}d}}(\\omega) (9) + S ​ ( ω ) ​ 𝐖 ​ ( ω ) ​ 𝐂 𝐫𝐫 ​ ( ω ) ​ 𝐖 H ​ ( ω ) ​ S ​ ( ω ) ∗ , \\displaystyle+S(\\omega)\\mathbf{W}(\\omega){{\\bf{C}}_{{\\bf{rr}}}}(\\omega)\\mathbf{W}^{\\mathrm{H}}(\\omega)S(\\omega)^{*}, where ( ⋅ ) H {(\\cdot)^{\\rm H}} is the Hermitian transpose operator, ( ⋅ ) ∗ {(\\cdot)^{*}} is the conjugation operator, C d ​ d ​ ( ω ) {{C}_{dd}}(\\omega) is the PSD of the disturbance, 𝐂 𝐫 ​ d ​ ( ω ) {{\\bf{C}}_{{\\bf{r}}d}}(\\omega) is the cross spectral density between the reference signal and the dis