sis assumes that the locations of the reference microphones, secondary source, and error microphone are fixed. The error signal in the frequency domain is represented as E ​ ( ω ) = D ​ ( ω ) − S ​ ( ω ) ​ 𝐖 ​ ( ω ) ​ 𝐑 ​ ( ω ) , E(\\omega)=D(\\omega)-S(\\omega)\\bf{W}(\\omega)\\bf{R}(\\omega), (8) where D ​ ( ω ) D(\\omega) is the frequency response of the disturbance, S ​ ( ω ) S(\\omega) is the secondary path, 𝐖 ( ω ) ∈ ℂ 1 × J \\mathbf{W}(\\omega)\\in\\mathbb{C}{{}^{1\\times J}} is the control filter, with ℂ 1 × J \\mathbb{C}{{}^{1\\times J}} representing a 1 × J 1\\times J vector of complex values, and 𝐑 ( ω ) ∈ ℂ J × 1 \\mathbf{R}(\\omega)\\in\\mathbb{C}{{}^{J\\times 1}} is the reference signal. To find the optimal control filter, the cost function is the power spectral density (PSD) of the error signal, given by J ​ ( ω ) \\displaystyle J(\\omega) = C d ​ d ​ ( ω ) − 𝐂 𝐫 ​ d ​ ( ω ) ​ 𝐖 H ​ ( ω ) ​ S ​ ( ω ) ∗ − S ​ ( ω ) ​ 𝐖 ​ ( ω ) ​ 𝐂 𝐫 ​ d H ​ ( ω ) \\displaystyle={{C}_{dd}}(\\omega)-{{\\bf{C}}_{{\\bf{r}}d}}(\\omega)\\mathbf{W}^{\\mathrm{H}}(\\omega)S(\\omega)^{*}-S(\\omega)\\mathbf{W}(\\omega){{\\bf{C}}^{\\mathrm{H}}_{{\\bf{r}}d}}(\\omega) (9) + S ​ ( ω ) ​ 𝐖 ​ ( ω ) ​ 𝐂 𝐫𝐫 ​ ( ω ) ​ 𝐖 H ​ ( ω ) ​ S ​ ( ω ) ∗ , \\displaystyle+S(\\omega)\\mathbf{W}(\\omega){{\\bf{C}}_{{\\bf{rr}}}}(\\omega)\\mathbf{W}^{\\mathrm{H}}(\\omega)S(\\omega)^{*}, where ( ⋅ ) H {(\\cdot)^{\\rm H}} is the Hermitian transpose operator, ( ⋅ ) ∗ {(\\cdot)^{*}} is the conjugation operator, C d ​ d ​ ( ω ) {{C}_{dd}}(\\omega) is the PSD of the disturbance, 𝐂 𝐫 ​ d ​ ( ω ) {{\\bf{C}}_{{\\bf{r}}d}}(\\omega) is the cross spectral density between the reference signal and the disturbance, and 𝐂 𝐫𝐫 ​ ( ω ) {{\\bf{C}}_{{\\bf{rr}}}}(\\omega) is the PSD of the reference signal, defined as C d ​ d ​ ( ω ) = 𝔼 ​ [ D ​ ( ω ) ​ D H ​ ( ω ) ] , {{C}_{dd}}(\\omega)=\\mathbb{E}[D(\\omega)D^{\\mathrm{H}}(\\omega)], (10) 𝐂 𝐫 ​ d ( ω ) = 𝔼 [ D ( ω ) 𝐑 H ( ω ) ] ∈ ℂ , 1 × J {{\\bf{C}}_{{\\bf{r}}d}}(\\omega)